	<entry>
		<title type="html"><![CDATA[Re: Correct Pronounciation of the Sun God "Surya"?]]></title>
		<link rel="alternate" href="http://spokensanskrit.de/board/forum/viewtopic.php?pid=5423#p5423"/>
		<content type="html"><![CDATA[<div class="quotebox"><cite>theunborn wrote:</cite><blockquote><div><p>In &#039;suu&#039; the &#039;uu&#039; is pronounced long. That is, very similar to &#039;oo&#039; in room, cool, bloom, broom, rook; very similar to &#039;a&#039; in ball, call, all. (Twice as long as the single unit of sound)</p><p>The &#039;r&#039; is pronounced very short. That is, very similar to &#039;r&#039; in curb, cork, etc.</p><p>It is definitely not &#039;suuriya&#039; - the &#039;i&#039; there should not be there.</p><p>The spelling in English language for Sanskrit words are only approximate. They were mostly devised by English rulers long ago and may not reflect the correct pronunciation of the words. E.g., In &#039;murti&#039; the &#039;u&#039; is two units long when pronounced even though there is only one &#039;u&#039; there. Indians pronounce &#039;murti&#039; properly because they know the correct pronunciation - it is the non-natives who have most difficulty in this aspect. [This is something like the name &#039;Tan&#039;, &#039;Chan&#039; in Chinese, I have been told. i.e., written differently in English but pronounced properly in Chinese]</p></div></blockquote></div><p>Thank you Unborn Sir. Most people support your point like this Yahoo Answer:</p><p>http://in.answers.yahoo.com/question/index?qid=20130916214308AAEySkw</p><p>I don&#039;t quite understand but anyway I will pronounce Suurya as the right way.</p>]]></content>
		<author>
			<name><![CDATA[photoarman]]></name>
			<uri>http://spokensanskrit.de/board/forum/profile.php?id=8569</uri>
		</author>
		<updated>2013-10-02T06:55:30Z</updated>
		<id>http://spokensanskrit.de/board/forum/viewtopic.php?pid=5423#p5423</id>
	</entry>
	<entry>
		<title type="html"><![CDATA[Re: Correct Pronounciation of the Sun God "Surya"?]]></title>
		<link rel="alternate" href="http://spokensanskrit.de/board/forum/viewtopic.php?pid=5422#p5422"/>
		<content type="html"><![CDATA[<p>In &#039;suu&#039; the &#039;uu&#039; is pronounced long. That is, very similar to &#039;oo&#039; in room, cool, bloom, broom, rook; very similar to &#039;a&#039; in ball, call, all. (Twice as long as the single unit of sound)</p><p>The &#039;r&#039; is pronounced very short. That is, very similar to &#039;r&#039; in curb, cork, etc.</p><p>It is definitely not &#039;suuriya&#039; - the &#039;i&#039; there should not be there.</p><p>The spelling in English language for Sanskrit words are only approximate. They were mostly devised by English rulers long ago and may not reflect the correct pronunciation of the words. E.g., In &#039;murti&#039; the &#039;u&#039; is two units long when pronounced even though there is only one &#039;u&#039; there. Indians pronounce &#039;murti&#039; properly because they know the correct pronunciation - it is the non-natives who have most difficulty in this aspect. [This is something like the name &#039;Tan&#039;, &#039;Chan&#039; in Chinese, I have been told. i.e., written differently in English but pronounced properly in Chinese]</p>]]></content>
		<author>
			<name><![CDATA[theunborn]]></name>
			<uri>http://spokensanskrit.de/board/forum/profile.php?id=228</uri>
		</author>
